               <p>Second Middlesex Jury, before Mr. Baron Gurney.</p>
               <p>431. 
               
                  <persName id="t18340220-113-defend1144" type="defendantName">
                     JOSEPH 
                     PURVIS
                  <interp inst="t18340220-113-defend1144" type="surname" value="PURVIS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-113-defend1144" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-113-defend1144" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
               
             was indicted for <rs id="t18340220-113-off655" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18340220-113-off655" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-113-off655" type="offenceSubcategory" value="theftFromPlace"></interp>
               stealing, on the <rs id="t18340220-113-cd656" type="crimeDate">6th of February</rs>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18340220-113-off655 t18340220-113-cd656"></join>, at St. Pancras, 2 coats, value 2l.; 2 waistcoats, value 15s.; 2 pair of trousers, value 14s.; 1 pair of shoes, value 11s.; and 1 handkerchief, value 1s.; the goods of 
                     
                        <persName id="t18340220-113-victim1146" type="victimName">
                           William 
                           Purvis
                        <interp inst="t18340220-113-victim1146" type="surname" value="Purvis"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18340220-113-victim1146" type="given" value="William"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18340220-113-victim1146" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     </persName>
                     
                   - and 1 coat, value 1l. 5s.; 1 pair of trousers, value 15s.; 1 waistcoat, value 10s.; and 1 pair of shoes, value 5s.; the goods of 
                     
                        <persName id="t18340220-113-victim1148" type="victimName">
                           Thomas 
                           Green
                        <interp inst="t18340220-113-victim1148" type="surname" value="Green"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18340220-113-victim1148" type="given" value="Thomas"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18340220-113-victim1148" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     </persName>
                     
                  , in his dwelling-house
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>WILLIAM PURVIS. I am the prisoner's brother - he lodged with me; and my brother-in-law Thomas Green lodged in the same house - we all lodged there - the prisoner left the house on Thursday evening, the 6th of February - I did not know of his intention to go - after he was<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183402200071"></xptr>gone, I missed two suits of clothes, a pair of shoes, and a handkerchief, all belonging to me - I saw him again on a Sunday evening, in the New-road - I went to him, in consequence of a message, and found him in the road, by King's-cross, I asked him where my clothes were - he said he had not destroyed only one suit - he said he had sold the blue suit and a pair of shoes for 10s. - I did not say he had better tell me about them - he asked what my determination was to do about it - I told him I had given it into the hands of the police, and that I could not alter it- he said he had pawned Green's suit for 1l. - I sent for the policeman, and gave him in charge - my clothes were worth 4l., all together - I had seen my things last in my box up stairs in our room - the prisoner and I slept in the same room - I was out at work when he went away.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340220-113-person1149">
                  THOMAS 
                  GREEN
               <interp inst="t18340220-113-person1149" type="surname" value="GREEN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-113-person1149" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-113-person1149" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am brother-in-law of the prosecutor - he lodged with me - I rent the house - the prisoner left the house on the evening of the 6th of February - I lost a coat, trowsers, waistcoat, and a pair of shoes, worth 2l. 15s. - they were up stairs, I think, in my chest - but I had not seen them for a fortnight - I missed them the evening he left - I did not know he intended to go away.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340220-113-person1150">
                  GEORGE 
                  CLARKSON
               <interp inst="t18340220-113-person1150" type="surname" value="CLARKSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-113-person1150" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-113-person1150" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am servant to Mr. Drew, a pawnbroker, and live at Clarke's-place, Islington - I received a suit of clothes in pawn from the prisoner, on the 6th of February, for 1l., in the name of Purdy.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340220-113-person1151">
                  JAMES 
                  WELLS
               <interp inst="t18340220-113-person1151" type="surname" value="WELLS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-113-person1151" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-113-person1151" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a policeman - I apprehended the prisoner, but found nothing on him.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. We were sitting together on Sunday evening - I asked them if they would allow me any money if I got a ship - they said they would, and I took the things to fit myself out with - I never took any clothes out of any box at all.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340220-113-person1152">
                  THOMAS 
                  GREEN
               <interp inst="t18340220-113-person1152" type="surname" value="GREEN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-113-person1152" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340220-113-person1152" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             re-examined. I said, if he wanted money at any time which would do him good, and I should not be in the way, any of my articles which he chose to take, he might pawn.</p>
               <p>WILLIAM PURVIS. I told him he might have my clothes if he asked my leave; but he did not ask my leave.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18340220-113-verdict657" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18340220-113-verdict657" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
               NOT GUILTY
            </rs>.</p>
